---
/**
 * applied-systems-design-fundamentals · Figure 2 — "the latency ladder".
 *
 * Copied VERBATIM from
 * docs/applied-systems-design/applied-systems-design-fundamentals.html
 * (the Level-2 figure: svg + figcaption incl. the footnote <sup>). It lives as an
 * .astro component, NOT inline in the MDX, because MDX's JSX parser is unreliable
 * with raw inline SVG using kebab-case attrs (text-anchor, font-size, …) and
 * <tspan>. This figure references no markers, so it needs no local <defs>.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 600 220"
        role="img"
        aria-label="The latency ladder: L1 1ns, RAM 100ns, SSD 100us, datacenter round-trip 0.5ms, disk seek 10ms, cross-region 100ms, each rung roughly 100x slower"
    >
        <g font-family="ui-sans-serif,system-ui,sans-serif">
            <text
                x="300"
                y="20"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="12"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#111110">THE LATENCY LADDER — four jumps of ~100×</text
            >
            <g font-size="10">
                <rect x="10" y="36" width="40" height="20" rx="4" fill="#eef5ee" stroke="#2f5d3a"
                ></rect><text x="60" y="51" fill="#111110"
                    >L1 cache · <tspan font-weight="700">1 ns</tspan></text
                >
                <rect x="10" y="64" width="70" height="20" rx="4" fill="#eef5ee" stroke="#2f5d3a"
                ></rect><text x="90" y="79" fill="#111110"
                    >RAM · <tspan font-weight="700">100 ns</tspan> &#160;(100×)</text
                >
                <rect x="10" y="92" width="130" height="20" rx="4" fill="#fbfaf2" stroke="#7a1f12"
                ></rect><text x="150" y="107" fill="#111110"
                    >SSD random read · <tspan font-weight="700">100 µs</tspan> &#160;(1000×)</text
                >
                <rect x="10" y="120" width="200" height="20" rx="4" fill="#fbfaf2" stroke="#1f3a5a"
                ></rect><text x="220" y="135" fill="#111110"
                    >DC round-trip · <tspan font-weight="700">0.5 ms</tspan></text
                >
                <rect x="10" y="148" width="300" height="20" rx="4" fill="#f7ecea" stroke="#9a2417"
                ></rect><text x="320" y="163" fill="#111110"
                    >disk seek · <tspan font-weight="700">10 ms</tspan></text
                >
                <rect x="10" y="176" width="430" height="20" rx="4" fill="#f7ecea" stroke="#9a2417"
                ></rect><text x="450" y="191" fill="#111110"
                    >cross-region · <tspan font-weight="700">100 ms</tspan> &#160;(physics)</text
                >
            </g>
            <text x="300" y="214" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="#6b675f"
                >RAM is ~200,000× faster than a cross-region hop → this is why every design has a
                cache</text
            >
        </g>
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        The takeaway is the <em>gaps</em>, not the digits. Memorise the four ~100× jumps; a cache
        buys a 1000× leap back up the ladder.<sup><a href="#s3" id="r3">3</a></sup>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
